rtist%20Leonardo%20Da%20Vinci.%20According%20to%20ground-breaking%20research%20released%20on%20Wednesday%20in%20the%20Journal%20of%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fpubs.acs.org%2Fdoi%2Fpdf%2F10.1021%2Fjacs.3c07000%5C%22%3EAmerican%20Chemical%20Society%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20the%20Renaissance%20painter%20invented%20a%20unique%20chemical%20formula%20for%20the%20oil%20paints%20he%20used%20in%20the%20painting.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EResearchers%20in%20France%20and%20Britain%20studied%20minuscule%20pieces%20from%20two%20of%20Da%20Vinci's%20most%20famous%20paintings%2C%20the%20Last%20Supper%20and%20Mona%20Lisa%20using%20X-rays%20and%20infrared%20spectroscopy%20to%20determine%20the%20chemical%20makeup%20of%20the%20artist's%20paint%20combination.%20In%20the%20layer%20beneath%20the%20artwork%2C%20the%20scientists%20found%20traces%20of%20lead%20oxide%2C%20an%20orange%20pigment%20that%20helped%20the%20paint%20dry%20and%20thicken%2C%20in%20addition%20to%20white%20lead%20pigment%20and%20oil.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EAs%20per%20the%20study%2C%20a%20lot%20of%20Da%20Vinci's%20artworks%2C%20including%20the%20Mona%20Lisa%2C%20were%20created%20on%20wooden%20panels.%20According%20to%20the%20study's%20findings%2C%20the%20artist%2C%20who%20was%20also%20an%20engineer%2C%20probably%20added%20the%20lead%20oxide%20to%20make%20an%20opaque%20undercoat%20that%20was%20thick%20enough%20to%20cover%20the%20wood.%20The%20study%20also%20demonstrates%20the%20public's%20enduring%20interest%20in%20the%20well-known%20painting%2C%20which%20is%20regarded%20as%20the%20classic%20Italian%20Renaissance%20work%20of%20art.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EFurthermore%2C%20researchers%20from%20the%20Centre%20National%20De%20La%20Recherche%20Scientifique%2C%20the%20premier%20scientific%20organisation%20in%20France%2C%20headed%20by%20chemist%20Victor%20Gonzalez%20went%20through%20Leonardo%20da%20Vinci's%20manuscripts%20to%20support%20the%20long-held%20theory%20that%20he%20used%20lead%20oxide%20in%20his%20paint%20mixture%2C%20but%20they%20were%20unable%20to%20find%20any%20conclusive%20evidence.%20Later%2C%20they%20found%20that%20the%20initial%20coat%20of%20paint%20contained%20a%20lead%20mineral%20known%20as%20plumbonacrite.%20According%20to%20them%2C%20the%20plumbonacrite%20formed%20as%20a%20result%20of%20a%20chemical%20reaction%20between%20the%20lead%20oxide%20and%20the%20oil.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EA%20few%20months%20ago%2C%20an%20Italian%20art%20researcher%20solved%20the%20mystery%20behind%20the%20stone%20bridge%20seen%20in%20the%20backdrop%20of%20the%20Mona%20Lisa%20painting.%20According%20to%20%3Cem%3EThe%20Guardian%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20the%20Italian%20historian%20Silvano%20Vinceti%20said%20he%20had%20no%20doubt%20that%20the%20Romito%20di%20Laterina%20bridge%20in%20the%20province%20of%20Arezzo%20was%20what%20Leonardo%20had%20painted%20into%20the%20countryside%20landscape%20behind%20the%20enigmatic%20Mona%20Lisa%2C%20which%20would%20end%20a%20mystery%20that%20has%20fuelled%20countless%20disputes%20over%20the%20years.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20news%20outlet%20further%20reported%20that%20Leonardo%20painted%20the%20Mona%20Lisa%20in%20Florence%20in%20the%20early%2016th%20century%2C%20and%20just%20like%20the%20distant%20background%2C%20much%20rumour%20surrounds%20the%20identity%20of%20the%20woman%20depicted%20in%20the%20oil%20painting%2C%20who%20is%20generally%20accepted%20to%20be%20Lisa%20del%20Giocondo.%3C%2Fp%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1697098380000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fc.ndtvimg.com%2F2023-10%2Fcesgv288_mona-lisa_625x300_12_October_23.jpg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ndtv.com%2Ffeature%2Fleonardo-da-vinci-invented-unique-chemical-formula-for-painting-mona-lisa-says-study-4473962%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22According%20to%20the%20study's%20findings%2C%20the%20artist%2C%20who%20was%20also%20an%20engineer%2C%20probably%20added%20the%20lead%20oxide%20to%20make%20an%20opaque%20undercoat%20that%20was%20thick%20enough%20to%20cover%20the%20wood.%22%2C%22author%22%3A%22%22%2C%22engagemen